 also conserves convexity (since I have shown in Q11 that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 conserves convexity), and we have shown this is class.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subset V$
\end_inset

 be a convex cone, and 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{*}=\{x\in V|\li x,y\ri\ge0,\forall y\in K\}$
\end_inset

 be the dual cone.
 Prove that the dual cone is a convex cone:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Solution:
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K^{*},y\in K,0\le\theta\le1$
\end_inset

.
 We need to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta a+(1-\theta)b\in K^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us look at 
\begin_inset Formula $\li\theta a+(1-\theta)b,y\ri\overset{\text{Inner product is linear in the first component}}{=}\theta\overset{\ge0}{\overbrace{\li a,y\ri}}+(1-\theta)\overset{\ge0}{\overbrace{\li b,y\ri}}\ge0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow\li\theta a+(1-\theta)b,y\ri\in K^{*}\rightarrow K^{*}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
